# SEO, Performance & Accessibility (Nuxt Hotel Sites)

Strict, repeatable standards. No scope beyond this document.

## 1. Nuxt SEO module usage

- Use the **latest** [`@nuxtjs/seo`](https://github.com/nuxt-modules/seo) (Nuxt SEO module); keep it upgraded with the Nuxt major you ship.
- Configure SEO **once** in `nuxt.config` / shared SEO config: site URL, default title template, default description, default OG/Twitter defaults, locale defaults as required.
- **Centralize** page metadata: composables, route meta, or layout-level defaults—**not** scattered `useHead` blobs that repeat the same keys.
- **Defaults**: every route must resolve title, description, and canonical (or explicit noindex) via defaults when CMS/data omits values—never leave empty critical tags silently.
- **No duplicates**: one canonical source per concern; do not stack conflicting `title`, `meta name="description"`, or `og:*` from multiple places for the same route. Merge/override in one layer only.

## 2. Heading & content structure

- **Exactly one `<h1>`** per page (visible main topic).
- **Order**: `h1` → `h2` → `h3` only; **do not skip levels** (e.g. no `h1` then `h3`).
- Headings describe **structure and meaning**, not visual size—use CSS for appearance.
- Copy: **short, structured, scannable** (paragraphs, lists); consistent density page to page where the template allows.
- **No keyword stuffing** in headings or body for SEO tricks.

## 3. Image SEO

- Every `<img>` and meaningful decorative pattern must have **`alt`** (empty `alt=""` only for truly decorative images).
- `alt` **describes the image** in context; no keyword lists or redundant site name spam.
- **File names**: lowercase, **kebab-case**, descriptive (e.g. `deluxe-king-room-window.jpg`).
- **Banned**: generic names like `image1.jpg`, `pic.png`, `untitled`.

## 4. Performance

- **Minimize** third-party scripts and heavy dependencies; add only with a clear product need.
- **Lazy-load** images below the fold (`loading="lazy"` and/or the stack’s image component lazy mode); prioritize LCP image.
- **No data fetching** in leaf UI components—pages, route loaders, or composables own async work (aligns with project architecture rules).
- Target **fast first load**: avoid blocking the main thread with large sync work on boot; split heavy client-only code.
- Keep components **small and cheap**: avoid unnecessary watchers, giant templates, or re-render churn without need.

## 5. Accessibility (ARIA + standards)

- Prefer **semantic HTML** (`nav`, `main`, `header`, `footer`, `button`, `a`, `label`, headings) before ARIA.
- Use **ARIA only when HTML is insufficient**; never duplicate native semantics (e.g. don’t `role="button"` on a native `<button>` without cause).
- **Inputs**: every control has an associated **`<label>`** (or `aria-labelledby` / `aria-label` only when label is visually hidden by design).
- **Buttons vs links**: `<button>` for actions; `<a href>` for navigation—don’t use `div` + click for those.
- **Keyboard**: all interactive elements reachable and operable with Tab / Enter / Space as appropriate; no positive `tabindex` traps except intentional widgets (dialogs, roving tabindex per pattern).
- **No ARIA misuse**: don’t slap random `role` / `aria-*` to silence warnings; fix the DOM instead.

## 6. Accessibility compliance

- Align with **WCAG 2.x** intent: perceivable, operable, understandable, robust—at **AA** for contrast and text sizing where applicable.
- **Contrast**: text and UI graphics meet **AA** minimums (4.5:1 normal text, 3:1 large/UI components unless design system documents exceptions).
- **Typography**: readable sizes and line length; avoid relying on color alone for meaning (use text, pattern, or icons + text).
- **Focus**: visible **focus indicators** on interactive elements; do not `outline: none` without an equivalent visible focus style.
- **Screen readers**: meaningful order in the DOM, live regions only when needed, status/errors exposed to assistive tech.
- **Keyboard-only**: full primary flows usable without a mouse (booking, nav, forms, modals).
